00:25:32,665 --> 00:25:36,901
        Ethan risks everything  
        to be with the woman    
        that he loves,          

453
00:25:36,903 --> 00:25:38,469
                but he fails.   

454
00:25:38,471 --> 00:25:40,170
            Why?                

455
00:25:40,172 --> 00:25:44,375
    Why would Wharton           
    have Ethan and Mattie fail? 

456
00:25:45,343 --> 00:25:47,545
        Anna? What do you think?

457
00:25:47,547 --> 00:25:49,113
I didn't read it.               

458
00:25:49,714 --> 00:25:51,181
    Did anybody read it?        

459
00:25:53,084 --> 00:25:56,453
    No. See, that's the thing   
    about literature--          

460
00:25:56,455 --> 00:25:58,155
    You have to read it.        

461
00:25:59,224 --> 00:26:02,359
        Okay. For tomorrow--    
[ School Bell Rings ]           

462
00:26:02,361 --> 00:26:05,162
    I want everyone             
    to finish <i>Ethan Frome.</i>      

463
00:26:06,565 --> 00:26:08,799
                    Lunch?      
    Sure.                       

464
00:26:10,302 --> 00:26:11,969
        I was talking to her.   

465
00:26:26,184 --> 00:26:28,485
[ Kristin ]                     
All I'm saying is               
that I can't think of a time... 

466
00:26:28,487 --> 00:26:31,855
when Lumpy wasn't either drunk  
or naked or both.               

467
00:26:31,857 --> 00:26:33,924
Yeah, everyone lets loose       
on vacation.                    

468
00:26:33,926 --> 00:26:37,094
    Clearly you've forgotten    
    about the hairy bead rack   
    incident on Bourbon St.     

469
00:26:37,096 --> 00:26:39,363
[ Chuckling ]                   
Oh, yeah.                       

470
00:26:39,365 --> 00:26:43,067
    I mean, New Orleans         
    was struggling through      
    a post-Katrina holocaust,   

471
00:26:43,069 --> 00:26:46,637
        and Lumpy thinks he can 
        brighten everyone's day 
        by hanging beads from-- 

472
00:26:46,639 --> 00:26:49,039
            What did he call it?
    His hairy button.           

473
00:26:49,041 --> 00:26:50,908
                Hairy button.   
That was hilarious.             

474
00:26:50,910 --> 00:26:52,610
                Oh, Scott.      
Okay, listen.                   
You know what?                  

475
00:26:52,612 --> 00:26:56,180
I agree with you.               
In the last year the drinking   
got a little out of control.    

476
00:26:56,182 --> 00:26:58,616
But I don't know                
what you want me to say, Kris.  

477
00:26:58,618 --> 00:27:01,952
I mean,                         
he was my best friend.          

478
00:27:01,954 --> 00:27:04,288
            But... he wasn't    
            your <i>best</i> friend.   

479
00:27:04,290 --> 00:27:06,824
            He was              
            your oldest friend. 

480
00:27:06,826 --> 00:27:08,826
        There's a difference.   

481
00:27:08,828 --> 00:27:10,828
I don't care                    
what you call him.              

482
00:27:10,830 --> 00:27:12,963
I knew Lumpy                    
better than anyone.             

483
00:27:15,367 --> 00:27:17,234
        I'm very sorry          
        for your loss,          

484
00:27:17,236 --> 00:27:20,604
    but Lawrence is no longer   
    a law student here.         

485
00:27:22,540 --> 00:27:24,842
What? N-No.                     
That must be a mistake.         

486
00:27:24,844 --> 00:27:27,711
        Well, he hasn't         
        been enrolled           
        for almost a year.      

487
00:27:27,713 --> 00:27:29,580
                    A year?     

488
00:27:29,582 --> 00:27:31,348
Did he transfer                 
to another school?              

489
00:27:31,350 --> 00:27:35,285
    I don't have any record     
    of a transcript request.    

490
00:27:35,287 --> 00:27:36,987
            He flunked out      
            of law school?      

491
00:27:36,989 --> 00:27:38,589
    Actually, his grades        
    were quite strong.          

492
00:27:38,591 --> 00:27:40,290
    He left                     
    for personal reasons.       

493
00:27:40,292 --> 00:27:41,892
What does that mean?            

494
00:27:41,894 --> 00:27:44,828
    I-I'm sorry.                
    I don't have                
    any further information.    

495
00:27:44,830 --> 00:27:49,500
But I'd be happy                
to put his funeral announcement 
on our Web site.                

496
00:27:49,502 --> 00:27:53,137
Uh, thank you--                 
Actually, could you search      
for one more student for us?    

497
00:27:53,139 --> 00:27:55,172
    It's a friend of Lumpy's.   

498
00:27:55,174 --> 00:27:57,675
            Lumpy?              
                Lawrence. Sorry.

499
00:27:57,677 --> 00:27:59,243
        Of course.              

500
00:27:59,245 --> 00:28:01,578
    Uh, what's the name?        

501
00:28:01,580 --> 00:28:03,380
    Uh, Ra--                    
                Ramsey Anderson.

502
00:28:03,382 --> 00:28:05,249
        [ Typing ]              
        I'll check.             

503
00:28:08,186 --> 00:28:12,623
    Sorry. Lots of Andersons.   
    No Ramsey.                  

504
00:28:15,593 --> 00:28:17,895
 You are my lover              
 <i> and I do like you </i>           

505
00:28:17,897 --> 00:28:19,963
        Yeah. This is it.       

506
00:28:19,965 --> 00:28:23,567
 What's the matter?            
 <i>Tell me what to do </i>           
            <i>[ Bell Jingles ]</i>    

507
00:28:23,569 --> 00:28:26,503
 [ Continues ]                 

508
00:28:26,505 --> 00:28:28,138
        - Hi.                   
        - Hi.                   

509
00:28:28,140 --> 00:28:30,074
Two?                            
    No, we're actually          
    not here to eat.            

510
00:28:30,076 --> 00:28:32,976
    Um, we're friends           
    of Lumpy's.                 

511
00:28:32,978 --> 00:28:34,411
[ Laughs ]                      

512
00:28:34,413 --> 00:28:37,314
Last time I saw Lumps           
we were totally wasted,         

513
00:28:37,316 --> 00:28:40,150
and we ended up--               

514
00:28:40,152 --> 00:28:41,719
N-Never mind.                   

515
00:28:41,721 --> 00:28:43,287
                How old are you?
    [ Stammers ]                

516
00:28:43,289 --> 00:28:45,789
    I'm afraid we have          
    some really bad news.       

517
00:28:45,791 --> 00:28:49,159
Uh, L-Lumpy passed away...      

518
00:28:49,161 --> 00:28:51,161
            over the weekend.   
    What?                       

519
00:28:51,163 --> 00:28:54,298
It was an accident.             
It was a very unfortunate       
accident.                       

520
00:28:54,300 --> 00:28:56,333
    We just wanted              
    to tell his manager...      

521
00:28:56,335 --> 00:28:58,001
    and let everyone know       
    about the funeral.          

522
00:28:58,003 --> 00:28:59,670
Oh, my God. He O.D.'d.          

523
00:28:59,672 --> 00:29:01,605
    No. No, no, no.             

524
00:29:01,607 --> 00:29:04,675
    Why would you think         
    he O.D.'d?                  
            He died on a cactus.

525
00:29:05,610 --> 00:29:07,211
            Can you tell        
            your manager...     

526
00:29:07,213 --> 00:29:09,379
        that we're here         
        to talk to him or her?  

527
00:29:09,381 --> 00:29:12,850
Uh, sure.                       
Lumpy hasn't worked here        
in a couple of months though.   

528
00:29:12,852 --> 00:29:14,318
                    He hasn't?  

529
00:29:14,320 --> 00:29:16,186
No, he was--                    
he was fired.                   

530
00:29:16,188 --> 00:29:18,021
            What?               

531
00:29:18,023 --> 00:29:21,925
        How could he fire Lumpy?
        Is he in there?         
You can't go in there!          

532
00:29:21,927 --> 00:29:23,327
Scott, don't do that.           
I swear to God.                 

533
00:29:23,329 --> 00:29:24,995
Bruce doesn't like              
to be interrupted.              

534
00:29:24,997 --> 00:29:27,364
             <i> [ Rock ]</i>         
<i>Oh, eureka.</i>                     

535
00:29:27,366 --> 00:29:29,867
                        What?   
                    Oh. God.    
                    Sorry.      

536
00:29:29,869 --> 00:29:32,703
- Um--                          
- You can't just barge in here. 

537
00:29:32,705 --> 00:29:35,205
I just wanted to talk to you,   
but I-I'll wait outside.        

538
00:29:38,343 --> 00:29:40,644
I think he needs a minute.      

539
00:29:45,150 --> 00:29:48,051
            He--                
            He was stealing?    

540
00:29:48,053 --> 00:29:49,887
Uh, we caught him               
on camera.                      

541
00:29:49,889 --> 00:29:52,556
            No. There's no way. 
            Not Lumpy.          

542
00:29:52,558 --> 00:29:55,559
Look, bartending                
is a cash business.             

543
00:29:55,561 --> 00:29:59,062
It happens, you know.           
Sooner or later,                
temptation wins out.            

544
00:29:59,064 --> 00:30:00,597
            Well, did you       
            call the police?    

545
00:30:00,599 --> 00:30:02,499
            Is there a report   
            that was filed      
            or something?       

546
00:30:02,501 --> 00:30:06,003
The owners wanted to,           
but I never did.                
                            Why?

547
00:30:06,005 --> 00:30:08,739
I think                         
he was in a bad place.          

548
00:30:08,741 --> 00:30:10,908
            What do you mean?   

549
00:30:10,910 --> 00:30:14,511
There was a lot of booze        
and, uh,                        

550
00:30:14,513 --> 00:30:17,047
some girl up north              
in, uh, Lutsen.                 

551
00:30:17,049 --> 00:30:19,883
    Do you remember her name,   
    by any chance?              

552
00:30:19,885 --> 00:30:21,919
Oh, man. Uh--                   

553
00:30:21,921 --> 00:30:24,154
                Was it Ramsey?  

554
00:30:24,156 --> 00:30:26,056
It-- Maybe. Yeah.               
That sounds right.              

555
00:30:26,058 --> 00:30:28,992
                Okay. Thank you 
                for your time.  

556
00:30:28,994 --> 00:30:30,761
            And sorry about     
            barging in again.   

557
00:30:30,763 --> 00:30:32,863
I'm real sorry                  
about your friend.              

558
00:30:32,865 --> 00:30:34,765
Everyone                        
liked Lumpy.                    
                        Yeah.   

559
00:30:34,767 --> 00:30:36,867
        - Good luck.            
        - Thank you.            

560
00:30:36,869 --> 00:30:39,203
            Don't touch it!     
            [ Coughs ]          

561
00:30:39,205 --> 00:30:41,271
                Thank you.      

562
00:30:45,410 --> 00:30:47,377
[ Birds Twittering ]            

563
00:30:49,380 --> 00:30:51,181
                    Hey.        

564
00:30:51,183 --> 00:30:52,749
Hey.                            

565
00:30:54,152 --> 00:30:56,220
                Aren't you      
                going to work?  

566
00:30:56,222 --> 00:30:59,356
I called Dan.                   
I told him                      
I wasn't feeling well.          

567
00:31:00,792 --> 00:31:03,627
                    Is he okay? 
Hmm?                            

568
00:31:03,629 --> 00:31:05,362
            Wasn't he in danger?

569
00:31:06,631 --> 00:31:09,333
You don't believe               
in Ms. Shirley, do you?         

570
00:31:09,335 --> 00:31:11,134
        She's from              
        Thief River Falls, Mom. 

571
00:31:11,136 --> 00:31:14,838
It is a gift.                   
She has a real gift.            

572
00:31:14,840 --> 00:31:17,507
        Yeah.                   
        For taking your money.  

573
00:31:17,509 --> 00:31:20,978
The first time                  
I talked to her,                
she knew everything about me.   

574
00:31:20,980 --> 00:31:23,380
Names.                          

575
00:31:23,382 --> 00:31:25,349
She knew names.                 
                [ Door Opens ]  

576
00:31:25,351 --> 00:31:28,318
    Have you ever heard         
    of caller I.D. and Google?  
                [ Door Closes ] 

577
00:31:31,489 --> 00:31:33,690
                Hi, baby.       
Hey.                            

578
00:31:35,627 --> 00:31:37,661
Can I talk to you?              

579
00:31:53,544 --> 00:31:55,145
            [ Chuckles ]        
            Did you get it?     

580
00:31:55,647 --> 00:31:56,980
    Tried.                      

581
00:31:56,982 --> 00:31:58,582
            What happened?      

582
00:31:58,584 --> 00:32:01,718
One of the security thingies    
went off and I got busted       
for shoplifting.                

583
00:32:01,720 --> 00:32:04,922
        But I told you to take  
        the security tags off.  

584
00:32:04,924 --> 00:32:06,723
    I did.                      

585
00:32:06,725 --> 00:32:08,292
Must have missed one.           

586
00:32:15,533 --> 00:32:17,534
        It's okay. It's okay.   

587
00:32:19,871 --> 00:32:23,540
            Did you, uh--       
            Did you say anything
            about me?           

588
00:32:23,542 --> 00:32:25,108
        No.                     
            You sure? You sure? 

589
00:32:25,110 --> 00:32:28,178
        'Cause you can tell me. 
        Just tell me.           
    I didn't.                   

590
00:32:30,581 --> 00:32:35,786
    Ramsey, we need this money. 
    Your mom won't ask,         
    but we <i>need</i> it.             

591
00:32:35,788 --> 00:32:37,387
How bad does she need it?       

592
00:32:38,790 --> 00:32:42,059
                I told you      
                it ain't for us.

593
00:32:42,061 --> 00:32:43,927
                    Look at me. 

594
00:32:43,929 --> 00:32:46,496
        I come back from        
        two back-to-back tours  
        in Iraq last year,      

595
00:32:46,498 --> 00:32:48,265
                and I got shit. 

596
00:32:48,267 --> 00:32:51,201
            No job, no degree,  
            no money-- nothin'. 

597
00:32:51,203 --> 00:32:55,272
        All I have is respect,  
        and from you            
        I'm gonna get respect.  

598
00:32:57,041 --> 00:33:01,378
- I asked you to do one thing,  
  one stupid little thing--     
- [ Cell Phone Buzzes ]         

599
00:33:01,380 --> 00:33:03,013
[ Buzzing Continues ]           
        and you messed it up.   

600
00:33:03,015 --> 00:33:06,283
Uh--                            
        What's this?            
        Where'd you get this?   

601
00:33:07,919 --> 00:33:10,954
A friend.                       
                    Nice friend?

602
00:33:11,656 --> 00:33:13,357
        Yeah.                   

603
00:33:17,528 --> 00:33:20,931
    I wonder what               
    you have to do for a friend 
    to get a phone like this.   

604
00:33:31,609 --> 00:33:33,643
            [ Whispering ]      
            Don't mess up again.

605
00:33:42,286 --> 00:33:44,321
[ Line Ringing ]                

606
00:33:45,690 --> 00:33:47,391
[ Woman's Voice ]               
Your call has been forwarded... 

607
00:33:47,393 --> 00:33:49,893
to an automated                 
voice-messaging system.         

608
00:33:50,395 --> 00:33:53,196
3-3-2--                         

609
00:33:58,636 --> 00:34:00,037
[ Beep ]                        

610
00:34:17,989 --> 00:34:20,157
        Would anyone like       
        some more wine?         

611
00:34:20,159 --> 00:34:21,958
    Yeah.                       
                    I would.    

612
00:34:21,960 --> 00:34:24,294
Your uncle and I                
are very happy...               

613
00:34:24,296 --> 00:34:27,531
to have a belated               
Christmas dinner                
with the newlyweds.             

614
00:34:27,533 --> 00:34:29,433
We're all glad you're here.     

615
00:34:29,435 --> 00:34:34,204
Too bad your brother had to fly 
straight back to Wilmington     
from Phoenix.                   

616
00:34:34,206 --> 00:34:37,874
    Helen, you should see       
    the house he bought.        

617
00:34:37,876 --> 00:34:41,745
        Oh, John's work         
        is just going so well.  

618
00:34:41,747 --> 00:34:45,315
    His company is exploiting   
    Chinese children into       
    making automotive paint.    

619
00:34:45,317 --> 00:34:47,117
Here we go                      
with all the green talk again.  

620
00:34:47,119 --> 00:34:50,887
    We are proud of you too,    
    being a teacher.            

621
00:34:50,889 --> 00:34:53,557
        Why would--             
        That's not what I'm--   
[ Chuckles ]                    

622
00:34:53,559 --> 00:34:55,692
    [ Stammers ]                
    Could somebody please pass  
    the Mrs. Dash?              

623
00:34:55,694 --> 00:34:58,261
            She might be hiding 
            with Mr. Dash.      

624
00:34:58,263 --> 00:35:01,031
    Oh, we don't know if there  
    is a <i>Mr.</i> Dash, Dad.         

625
00:35:01,033 --> 00:35:04,534
    Maybe things didn't go well 
    after their wedding         
    or something.               

626
00:35:04,536 --> 00:35:07,137
Well, maybe Mr. Dash            
had some things on his mind,    

627
00:35:07,139 --> 00:35:09,706
            and things he had   
            to take care of.    

628
00:35:09,708 --> 00:35:11,975
    I just wonder               
    if Mr. and Mrs. Dash        
    didn't go on a honeymoon... 

629
00:35:11,977 --> 00:35:13,710
        and then after that     
        stop communicating.     

630
00:35:13,712 --> 00:35:15,545
Maybe Mrs. Dash should stop     
feeling sorry for herself.      

631
00:35:15,547 --> 00:35:19,549
I think that Mrs. Dash          
is trying really hard and maybe 
feels underappreciated.         

632
00:35:19,551 --> 00:35:22,819
Maybe Mrs. Dash should remember 
she's not the only spice        
in the spice rack.              

633
00:35:22,821 --> 00:35:24,988
            I'm not saying      
            that Mrs. Dash      
            is the only spice.  

634
00:35:24,990 --> 00:35:28,258
Mrs. Dash has gotten            
very arrogant lately.           
Little one-sided.               

635
00:35:28,260 --> 00:35:30,227
                    Arrogant?   
    Mm-hmm.                     

636
00:35:30,229 --> 00:35:33,096
There's paprika,                
there's thyme, there's rosem--  
a lot of other spices.          

637
00:35:33,098 --> 00:35:35,999
    I think maybe it's time     
    to clear the table.         

638
00:35:36,001 --> 00:35:38,735
        - I'll help you.        
        - No, no, Helen.        
          Now, you sit.         

639
00:35:38,737 --> 00:35:42,339
            I only get to wash  
            the Christmas dishes
            once a year.        

640
00:35:42,341 --> 00:35:44,040
Okay, this is it.               

641
00:35:50,414 --> 00:35:53,483
We couldn't believe             
all those strange-looking plants
in Phoenix.                     

642
00:35:53,485 --> 00:35:55,218
What were they called again?    

643
00:35:55,220 --> 00:35:57,254
            Cactus, Helen.      
            They were cactus.   

644
00:35:57,256 --> 00:35:59,556
They weren't cactus.            
I know what cactus look like.   

645
00:35:59,558 --> 00:36:01,758
They're succulents.             

646
00:36:05,363 --> 00:36:07,864
Too bad about your--            
your friend, Scott.             

647
00:36:07,866 --> 00:36:10,934
[ Uncle ]                       
Yeah. I'm sorry.                
That's too bad.                 

648
00:36:12,069 --> 00:36:14,571
    It was an unfortunate lesson
    for all of us.              

649
00:36:14,573 --> 00:36:16,773
            [ Roger ]           
            Boy looked like     
            he was a lot of fun.

650
00:36:16,775 --> 00:36:19,576
He was a lot of fun, Roger.     

651
00:36:19,578 --> 00:36:21,144
He wasn't a boy though.         

652
00:36:21,146 --> 00:36:23,947
He was a man.                   
    Of course he was a man.     

653
00:36:23,949 --> 00:36:26,383
No, no, no.                     
He was a real man.              

654
00:36:26,385 --> 00:36:28,485
Just because he drank           
a little too much...            

655
00:36:28,487 --> 00:36:30,654
and quit law school             
and he got fired from his job,  

656
00:36:30,656 --> 00:36:32,289
it doesn't make him             
less of a man.                  

657
00:36:32,291 --> 00:36:34,257
'Cause he was a <i>man,</i> Kris.      

658
00:36:34,259 --> 00:36:36,960
    Okay. We understand         
    and we know you're upset--  

659
00:36:36,962 --> 00:36:38,662
You asked me to pee             
sitting down!                   

660
00:36:38,664 --> 00:36:40,897
        I thought it would be   
        a nice compromise.      

661
00:36:40,899 --> 00:36:42,799
    You wanted me               
    to carry a purse,           
    for Christ's sake.          

662
00:36:42,801 --> 00:36:45,835
        - Why would he carry    
          a purse?              
        - It was a man bag!     

663
00:36:45,837 --> 00:36:48,605
    And I was only pointing out 
    that some men have          
    found it efficient.         

664
00:36:48,607 --> 00:36:50,340
            They are in Europe, 
            mostly--            
We don't live in Europe.        

665
00:36:50,342 --> 00:36:54,644
This is what                    
I'm talking about.              
Lumpy kept it real.             

666
00:36:54,646 --> 00:36:56,313
He was a man.                   

667
00:37:03,454 --> 00:37:06,156
    I'm going to help Mom       
    in the kitchen.             

668
00:37:06,657 --> 00:37:08,225
Good idea.                      

669
00:37:09,694 --> 00:37:12,829
    Come on, Terry.             
    This isn't even gonna       
